KEYBOARD SHORTCUTS:

  1. Assignment operator (<-) is Alt+- for Windows and Option+- for Mac
  2. Insert new code chunk Ctrl+Alt+I for Windows and Command+Option+I for Mac
  3. Run a line of code Ctrl+Enter for Windows and Command+Enter for Mac
  4. Run all the code within a chunk Ctrl+Shift+Enter for Windows and Command+Shift+Enter for Mac
  5. Insert a pipe operator (%>%) Ctrl+Shift+M for Windows and Command+Shift+M for Mac

  1. The $ notation is used in base R to pull out columns from a data frame. Its usage is as follows df$columnName, where df is the dataframe (or tibble) you are interested in pulling a column denoted by columnName from. Use this syntax to pull out the carrier column from the flights tibble and store it in a variable called flightCarrier.
flightCarrier <- flights$carrier

length(flightCarrier) == nrow(flights)

  1. Use the unique() function on the flightCarrier variable you created in the previous step to find the unique list of carriers in the flights dataset. Replace the flightCarrier with this new vector of unique values.

rr flightCarrier <- unique(flightCarrier) flightCarrier

  1. Print the new length of the flightCarrier vector.

rr length(flightCarrier)

  1. Get the data type of the flightCarrier vector using typeof(), is it the same as the type denoted in str(). (The output from the str() function abbreviates the type so for instance integer is denoted as int.)

  1. Use pipes to combine steps 2 and 4. Like so df$columnName %>% unique().
flightCarrier <- flights$carrier %>% 
  unique("carrier")
flightCarrier
 [1] "UA" "AA" "B6" "DL" "EV" "MQ" "US" "WN" "VX" "FL" "AS" "9E" "F9" "HA" "YV" "OO"
  1. Use the pull() function instead of the $ notation to achieve the same result as above. Save this as pulledCarrier
pulledCarrier <- pull(flights, "carrier") %>% 
  unique("carrier")
pulledCarrier
 [1] "UA" "AA" "B6" "DL" "EV" "MQ" "US" "WN" "VX" "FL" "AS" "9E" "F9" "HA" "YV" "OO"
  1. Use this function identical() to establish that the pulledCarrier and flightCarrier are the same.
identical(flightCarrier, pulledCarrier, num.eq = TRUE)
[1] TRUE
  1. Now try the same step as 8 with select() instead of pull. Save this as selectedCarrier
selectedCarrier <- flights %>% 
  select(carrier) %>% 
  unique()
selectedCarrier
  1. Use the identical() function to establish that selectedCarrier and flightCarrier are not the same.
identical(flightCarrier, selectedCarrier, num.eq = TRUE)
[1] FALSE
  1. Why aren’t selectedCarrier and flightCarrier identical? Think about the data structure that select() returns compared to that for pull()/$ The selectedCarrier and flightCarrier data are not identical because the select command returns a column of data in a table and the ‘$’ command simply returns the carrier data.

I had to use quotes around the carrier column name with the pull()/$ commands, but not with the select command. I’m not sure why this is and does this also play into the answer to this question?

  1. Which airports had the most number of flights that were delayed by more than 10 minute in 2013? (You can show a table with the counts of flights delayed by more than 10 minutes from each origin that is sorted in descending order of the count)
flights %>%

  1. Create a new variable timeLostInAir that is the difference between arrival delay and departure delay. Save this to a variable.
flightsPlus <- flights %>% 
  mutate(timeLostInAir = arr_delay - dep_delay)
flightsPlus
  1. Use the tibble saved in task 4 to find the flight that lost the most amount of time while in air
flightsPlus %>%

  1. Use the tibble saved in task 4 to show the top 5 carriers in the terms of timeLostInAir
flightsPlus%>%

Day 4

  1. Use a ggplot chart(s) (of your choice) to show the carriers that made up the most of amount of time in terms of departure delays. Say a flight is departs 10 minutes late but lands only 2 minutes late then timeMadeUp = 8, similarly if a flight that departs 20 minutes late but lands say 10 minutes early, then timeMadeUp = 30. (Only look at flights that were delayed for this, we are not interested in flights that departed early or on time.)
flights %>% 
  filter(dep_delay > 0) %>% 
  mutate(timeMadeUp = dep_delay - arr_delay, na.rm = T) %>% 
  group_by(carrier) %>% 
  summarise(avgTimeMadeUp = mean(timeMadeUp, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = carrier, y = avgTimeMadeUp)) +
    geom_col()

  1. Use a ggplot chart(s) (of your choice) to show the relationship between flight distance and arrival delay. (The flight distances are about the same for every flight, so you could consider using it as a group to summarise the data)
flights %>% 
  group_by(distance) %>% 
  summarise(avgArrDelay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = distance, y = avgArrDelay)) +
    geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Day 6

  1. Pick any chart you have made so far and make it publication ready
    • Add labels and titles
    • Add the following subtitle to it: “A chart I made for the daily tasks”
    • Try out a new theme from the ggthemes package
  2. Save this chart and share it on #general channel on slack
  3. Preview this notebook and push your changes to github. Share the link with me (personally on Slack) before 6:00 PM EST, Tuesday, April 2nd
library(ggthemes)
flights %>% 
  filter(dep_delay > 0) %>% 
  mutate(timeMadeUp = dep_delay - arr_delay, na.rm = T) %>% 
  group_by(carrier) %>% 
  summarise(avgTimeMadeUp = mean(timeMadeUp, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = carrier, y = avgTimeMadeUp)) +
    geom_col() +
  labs(
        x = "Airline",
        y = "Average Time Made Up In Air (minutes)",
        title = "A Majority of Airlines Make Up for Departure Delays in Air", 
        subtitle = "A chart I made for the daily tasks") +
    theme_hc()
